ass="sc-fmciRz bheIgq pf-576_ pf-lg-hide pf-md-hide pf-sm-hide"><div style="--cw:1170px" class="sc-gjNHFA gwWIgj"><div class="sc-ezbkAF A-dmbO pf-577_ pf-r pf-r-eh" style="--s-xs:15px" data-pf-type="Row"><div class="pf-c" style="--c-xs:12;--c-md:12;--c-lg:12"><div data-pf-type="Column" class="sc-gUQvok iVVDxu pf-578_"><div class="sc-ezbkAF A-dmbO pf-579_ pf-r pf-r-eh" style="--s-xs:15px" data-pf-type="Row"><div class="pf-c" style="--c-xs:12;--c-md:12;--c-lg:12"><div data-pf-type="Column" class="sc-gUQvok iVVDxu pf-580_"><h2 tabindex="0" spellcheck="false" data-pf-type="Heading2" class="sc-dPiLbb JgHoc pf-581_">FAQ for Subcision Cellulite Treatment</h2><p class="sc-jtXEFf jydWoQ pf-583_" data-pf-type="Paragraph"><span data-pf-type="Text" class="sc-jKTccl dCeBIC pf-585_">Is cellulite subcision safe?<span style="font-weight: 700;"></span></span></p><p class="sc-jtXEFf jydWoQ pf-586_" data-pf-type="Paragraph"><span data-pf-type="Text" class="sc-jKTccl dCeBIC pf-588_">Cellulite subcision, when performed correctly by an experienced doctor or surgeon, is considered quite safe. That said, as with any invasive procedure, it still has its side effects and risks, including bruising, scarring, and infection.&nbsp;&nbsp;<span style="font-weight: 700;"></span></span></p><p class="sc-jtXEFf jydWoQ pf-589_" data-pf-type="Paragraph"><span data-pf-type="Text" class="sc-jKTccl dCeBIC pf-591_">How much does cellulite subcision cost?<span style="font-weight: 700;"></span></span></p><p class="sc-jtXEFf jydWoQ pf-592_" data-pf-type="Paragraph"><span data-pf-type="Text" class="sc-jKTccl dCeBIC pf-594_">Cellulite subcision usually costs between $2500 and $6000. The main price-deciding factor is how many cellulite dimples you’d like to treat - the more widespread the cellulite, the more you’ll need to pay.&nbsp;<br>As with any aesthetic treatments, costs can also vary pretty widely from location to location. It’s always better to pay a little more for a more experienced and reputable surgeon or doctor.<span style="font-weight: 700;"></span></span></p><p class="sc-jtXEFf jydWoQ pf-595_" data-pf-type="Paragraph"><span data-pf-type="Text" class="sc-jKTccl dCeBIC pf-597_">How long do the results of cellulite subcision last?<span style="font-weight: 700;"></span></span></p><p class="sc-jtXEFf jydWoQ pf-598_" data-pf-type="Paragraph"><span data-pf-type="Text" class="sc-jKTccl dCeBIC pf-600_">The results from subcision alone can last for at least a few years. Most research looks at results two years after treatment, but many doctors report that the skin can still appear smooth for three to five years after treatment.&nbsp;<span style="font-weight: 700;"></span></span></p><p class="sc-jtXEFf jydWoQ pf-601_" data-pf-type="Paragraph"><span data-pf-type="Text" class="sc-jKTccl dCeBIC pf-603_">Who is a good candidate for cellulite subcision treatment?<span style="font-weight: 700;"></span></span></p><p class="sc-jtXEFf jydWoQ pf-604_" data-pf-type="Paragraph"><span data-pf-type="Text" class="sc-jKTccl dCeBIC pf-606_">The best candidate for subcision is someone with moderate to severe cellulite who is otherwise at a stable weight. There are actually grades that professionals use to analyze cellulite.<br><br>Subcision is best for those with grade two or grade three cellulite. That means that your dimples are visible no matter how your body is positioned, as opposed to those with grade one that might only have visible cellulite when sitting or pinching their skin.<br><br>As for contraindications, subcision is not recommended for pregnant women, anyone who’s very prone to scarring, those suffering from bleeding disorders or who are taking medications that prevent blood clotting, and more. Your surgeon should consult a thorough consultation with you to make sure that you’re a good candidate.&nbsp;<span style="font-weight: 700;"></span></span></p></div></div></div></div></div></div></div></div><div data-section-id="pf-943b" data-pf-type="Section" class="sc-fmciRz bheIgq